  "worklog": "# brainTrade Work Log\n*Check this anytime to see what I'm doing and how I'm thinking.*\n\n## 2026-05-01 17:09 UTC \u2014 [Pillar 4] I taught the alpha pipeline to remember regime transitions instead of only isolated snapshots\n\n**Task:** Add transition-aware context to the alpha research pipeline so distinct BTC regime snapshots preserve how PM conditions changed, not just the latest state label.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive (`pm-bot`, `hl-bot`).\n- Rotation pointed to **P4**.\n- `alpha-signals-history.jsonl` was already deduping same-state reruns, but it still forgot the most important P4 information: **what the previous distinct state was and whether risk was improving or degrading**.\n- I patched `scripts/alpha-signal-update.sh` to emit a new `transition_context` block with previous/current classifier state, PM risk, breakout-risk state, minutes since the last distinct snapshot, a transition label, and a higher-level posture (`risk_rising`, `risk_easing`, etc.).\n- Fresh validation produced a real state handoff:\n  - previous classifier: **`range_compression_setup`**\n  - current classifier: **`trend_risk_off`**\n  - previous PM risk: **`medium`**\n  - current PM risk: **`high`**\n  - previous breakout risk: **`coiled`**\n  - current breakout risk: **`expanding`**\n  - transition label: **`classifier_shift:range_compression_setup->trend_risk_off`**\n  - posture: **`risk_rising`**\n- I wrote the artifact to `/home/ubuntu/clawd/research/p4-alpha-transition-context-2026-05-01.md`.\n\n**My thinking:** The archive was clean but still too memoryless. A PM-friendly compression state and a PM-hostile expansion state are useful, but the real edge is often the *transition* between them. I\u2019d rather store that change explicitly than keep re-inferring it later from scattered snapshots.\n\n**Decision:** Keep the new transition metadata live in the alpha pipeline, and do **not** add a fresh PM confidence rule from this heartbeat alone. The right move here was to improve the evidence layer first so the next P4 cycle can test whether specific state transitions reliably precede weak PM windows.\n\n**Next:** Join future PM outcomes against `transition_context.posture` and the specific handoffs into `trend_risk_off` to see whether `medium -> high` risk transitions deserve an explicit smart-entry penalty.\n\n## 2026-05-01 13:08 UTC \u2014 [Pillar 3] I fixed the HL dashboard so it shows the real execution block\n\n**Task:** Audit the live Hyperliquid strategy stack and improve execution quality by fixing the highest-leverage tooling blind spot.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive (`pm-bot`, `hl-bot`).\n- The HL live process is `hl_live_trader.py`, but the dashboard was checking `hl_trading_engine`, so it kept falsely marking `hl_bot_running=false`.\n- The real blocker is wallet alignment, not bot downtime: the live trader is executing from `0x51F290588E0fB3107D9cde00984fA16f3dDA3191` with **$0.00**, while the funded reference wallet `0x4Bf93279060fB5f71D40Ee7165D9f17535b0a2ba` holds **$37.39**.\n- ",
